The Presidential Human Rights Council (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of the Presidents of the courts and to introduce their election.
For the Courts of Appeals and cassation, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also present his proposals within the framework of a presidential mandate.
The HRC has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work of the HRC was conducted on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with the members of the Council.
At a meeting with members of the Council on December 8, 2016, there were discussed some cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see "Kommersant" of 9 December).
The HRC's work resulted in 25 proposals, which concern both the independence of judges and the identification of judicial errors and the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights activists is to restrict the powers of the Presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the post of judge successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, the President of the Court, according to the HRC, must submit it to the appointment without the right to refuse, as the law currently permits.
It is also proposed to deprive the President of the right to allocate cases to judges.
To do this, allow experts, a specially written computer program can be written.
Also, the HRC considers that the President is not entitled to "predetermine the results of the qualification of the judge, to initiate his disciplinary proceedings, to make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments."
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to "the election of the Presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "to give them powers for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation."
Now all the Presidents of the courts (from Republican to district) are appointed for six years by the President on the presentation of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRC proposes a reorganisation of appeal and cassation in the courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation, not at the level of regional courts in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the courts."
Experts take the practice of arbitration courts.
There are "judicial districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee that this is a great independence from regional officials who are difficult to use "telephone law."
The justices of the HRC are proposing to strengthen the people's assessors so as to consider certain "categories of civil and administrative cases."
For example, the deprivation of parental rights, the restoration of work, the protection of honour and dignity, the deprivation of driving rights, etc.
"These are only our proposals," explained "Kommersant" member, Judge of the Constitutional Court, retired Tamara morshkova.
