Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help ease the OVC.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: diet, rich in meat proteins and dairy products, can help alleviate the symptoms of those who suffer from inflammatory diseases of the intestines.
This is an incurable disease, which affects about 1.3 million people in the USA and 300,000 in Great Britain, leads to the Coles and the abdominal fat, chronic or bloody nose, loss of weight and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to mitigate the symptoms of patients, it is advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington have determined that the main amino acid protein triptophan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase the tolerance of the intestines.
Dr. Marco Colonna, a leading researcher, explained that the immune cells in the intestines ensure that the harmful microbes coming from food do not penetrate into the body.
Cells capable of launching an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too strongly disturbed in the direction of inflammation, it may lead to inflammatory diseases of the intestines.
Experiments have shown that mice with some bacteria in the intestines appear to increase the tolerance of the cell.
And this bacteria need tryptophan - one of the building elements of protein - to start the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal microbioma of the intestines, and the development of cells that increase tolerance.
The more triptophan was contained in the diet of mice, the more these immune cells were."
He suggested that the same would work for people: the combination of L. reuteri and the rich triptophon diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammatory environment in the intestines.
Dr. Luisa Cervantes barraganas, who studied the variety of increasing the tolerance of the immune cells, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same line but was held separately, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the Microbiologists of the intestines - the bacteria, viruses and fungi, which usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA cells of the intestines were sequenced, and there were six types of bacteria present in mice with immune cells, but absent from mice that do not have them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microphobia and did not develop this type of immune cells have received L. reuteri, and the immune cells have appeared.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers have grown L. reuteri in the liquid environment and then moved small portions of the liquid - without bacteria - to the underdeveloped immune cells allocated from mice.
The immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the processing of triptophan, known as indol-3-lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the number of triptophan in mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was reduced by half, the number of cells has also fallen twice.
Dr. Servantes Barragan explains that people have the same increasing tolerance of the cell as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of triptophan from L. reuteri develop cell development in humans as in mice, but people suffering from inflammatory diseases of the intestines have found defects in the genes associated with triptophan.
She says: "Perhaps the development of these cells we need to be strengthened, since these cells depend on the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the cyshock.
High levels of triptophan, with L. reuteri, can potentially lead to the expansion of their population."
